<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="continuous-discovery">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-manager</domain>
    <summary>Integrate discovery as a recurring operational cadence: 15-20% capacity per sprint, three parallel loops (daily/weekly/sprint), and leakage check keeping delivery anchored to user problems.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>discovery</tag>
      <tag>product-research</tag>
      <tag>opportunity-solution-tree</tag>
      <tag>user-interviews</tag>
      <tag>cadence</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Continuous Discovery</title>
    <summary>Integrate discovery as a recurring operational cadence rather than a one-time project-start activity. Allocate 15-20% of team capacity to discovery every sprint. Run three loops in parallel: daily behaviour-watcher (analytics diffs), weekly user-interview cycle with synthesis into a tagged research repository, and sprint-cadence opportunity-mapper updating the opportunity-solution tree. Every shipped feature must be traceable to a tagged opportunity; leakage above 30% is a signal that delivery has decoupled from discovery.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Discovery treated as a phase produces stale insights that cannot keep up with a product in motion. Without a recurring cadence, the same problems are "rediscovered" quarterly, and shipped features pile up without evidence of user impact. Continuous discovery closes the loop: behavioural data feeds experiment hypotheses, interview themes inform prioritization, and the opportunity-solution tree keeps delivery anchored to real user problems rather than internal requests.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Product is past initial PMF and decisions have started feeling arbitrary; recurring discovery is needed to keep direction grounded.</item>
        <item>A delivery team has bandwidth to allocate ~15-20% to discovery without halting feature work.</item>
        <item>High-velocity environment (multiple releases per week) where one-off discovery cycles cannot keep pace.</item>
        <item>After a major launch, to monitor activation/retention while iterating.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-PMF: continuous discovery dilutes effort across a wide problem space; concentrated discovery sprints work better.</item>
        <item>Solo founder with no recurring user pool yet — there is nothing to continuously sample.</item>
        <item>Frozen feature scope with imminent contractual deadline; findings cannot be acted on.</item>
        <item>Teams without analytics and a research repository; insights evaporate without structured storage.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="three-discovery-loops">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run three loops in parallel: daily behaviour-watcher (analytics diffs, anomaly digests), weekly interview cycle with repository tagging, sprint-cadence opportunity-mapper updating the opportunity-solution tree.</statement>
        <rationale>Each loop captures a different signal type at the right frequency. Collapsing all three into one weekly meeting misses fast behavioural signals and buries slow qualitative ones.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Daily loop output: route digests to humans only on threshold breaches, not on every metric movement. Continuous monitoring produces alert fatigue without threshold gates.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents running 24/7 without threshold gates flood teams with noise, causing discovery fatigue that mirrors the problem it was meant to solve.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="capacity-rule">
      <rule>
        <statement>Allocate 15-20% of team capacity to discovery every sprint. Ship at least one experiment per sprint, even small ones. Cadence beats perfection.</statement>
        <rationale>Discovery allocated to "leftover time" is the first thing cut when delivery pressure rises. Hard capacity allocation makes it visible in sprint planning.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="research-repository">
      <rule>
        <statement>Tag every interview snippet to an opportunity in a single repository. Without tagging, continuous discovery is continuous chatter. Maintain a rolling participant panel of 30-50 users with rotation to prevent sample bias.</statement>
        <rationale>The same lesson "rediscovered" quarterly is a sign of a discovery practice with no memory. A tagged repository converts recurring insight cost into a one-time investment.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Combine at least two signal types per discovery theme: interview data alone, behavioural data alone, or support tickets alone are insufficient triangulation.</statement>
        <rationale>Users say one thing and do another. Single-source discovery over-indexes on expressed rather than revealed preference.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="leakage-check">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every shipped feature must be traceable to a tagged opportunity in the research repository. Leakage (shipped features with no linked opportunity) above 30% signals delivery has decoupled from discovery.</statement>
        <rationale>High leakage means the team is building based on internal opinion rather than discovered user need, negating the investment in continuous discovery.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/check-leakage.py">Python script that computes leakage ratio and exits non-zero above 30%.</reference>
    </section>
    <section name="triangulation-rule">
      <rule>
        <statement>Hold a monthly "what changed in user behaviour" review using analytics diffs, not anecdotes. Compare against trailing 4 weeks, not last 7 days, to filter seasonality.</statement>
        <rationale>7-day comparisons trigger false anomalies on weekends and holidays. Trailing 4-week baseline absorbs normal weekly patterns.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Discovery theatre: weekly interviews held but never tied back to decisions. The cadence tracks attendance, not impact.</description>
        <reason>Discovery that generates insights nobody acts on wastes researcher time and erodes team confidence in the practice. Require each interview cycle to produce at least one tagged opportunity or a documented null result.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Same 5 power users interviewed every week, producing a confirmation chamber.</description>
        <reason>Power users are not representative users. Their advanced usage patterns actively mislead feature prioritization. Rotate the participant panel on a fixed schedule.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Discovery and delivery teams operating as separate units: discovery becomes a wishlist generator nobody implements.</description>
        <reason>Discovery findings must map directly to the team that makes build decisions. Separate org structures create a handoff gap where insights are filtered by priority politics.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Synthesis agent over-summarises: many distinct interview quotes collapse into 2-3 generic themes.</description>
        <reason>Generic themes lose actionable signal. Set a minimum number of distinct themes and require evidence count per theme before accepting synthesis output.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sentiment classifier reports high confidence on small samples (n less than 15).</description>
        <reason>Statistical significance requires sufficient sample size. Refuse confidence above 0.8 below n=15 and flag sample size in all synthesis output.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents recommend "schedule more interviews" as the remedy for any gap in understanding.</description>
        <reason>Interviews are expensive. Behavioural data and support ticket analysis should be the first resort; interviews are the escalation path when data is ambiguous.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent pushes interview transcripts with interviewee names to shared repositories without redaction.</description>
        <reason>PII leakage via research tools is a trust and legal risk. Add a scrubber step before any transcript touches an external repo.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Schedule three loops. Daily: a behaviour-watcher agent diffs analytics dashboards (PostHog, Mixpanel, Amplitude) and drops anomalies into a digest. Weekly: an interview-prep agent picks 5 candidate users by segment, drafts an interview guide tied to current opportunities; after sessions, a transcription/synthesis agent extracts themes and tags them in a research repository (Dovetail/Notion). Sprint cadence: an opportunity-mapper agent updates the opportunity-solution tree feeding the roadmap. Humans run the actual interviews and decide which experiments graduate to delivery.</p>
      <section name="recommended-subagents">
        <list>
          <item>faion-idea-generator-agent — generates experiment hypotheses from the latest week's themes.</item>
          <item>faion-mlp-impl-planner-agent — promotes validated opportunities into roadmap initiatives.</item>
          <item>faion-spec-reviewer-agent — reviews experiment briefs for testability before launch.</item>
          <item>faion-task-creator-agent — turns approved experiments into trackable backlog items.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <prompt purpose="discovery-synthesizer"><![CDATA[System: You are a discovery synthesizer. Input: array of interview snippets,
support ticket excerpts, and analytics anomalies. Output JSON:
  {themes:[{label, evidence:[{source, quote_or_metric}], confidence:0..1}],
   opportunities:[{label, parent_theme, jtbd, severity:lo|md|hi}],
   suggested_experiments:[{hypothesis, method, sample_n, success_metric,
   kill_threshold}]}
Forbid summarising more than 5 themes. Reject opportunities lacking
  >=2 distinct evidence sources.]]></prompt>
      <prompt purpose="discovery-cadence-auditor"><![CDATA[System: You are a discovery cadence auditor. Given last 30 days of activity,
return: {interviews_completed, themes_logged, experiments_run,
shipped_decisions_traced_to_themes, leakage_pct}.
Flag if shipped_decisions_traced_to_themes < 50% of feature releases.]]></prompt>
    </section>
    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>posthog API — Programmatic dashboard diffs, anomaly alerts. https://posthog.com/docs/api</item>
        <item>mixpanel-api — Same for Mixpanel; cohort comparisons. https://developer.mixpanel.com</item>
        <item>amplitude-sdk — Behavioural cohorts → discovery prompts. https://www.docs.developers.amplitude.com</item>
        <item>dovetail API — Push tagged research notes from agents. https://developers.dovetail.com</item>
        <item>whisper.cpp / openai whisper — Local transcription for interview audio. https://github.com/openai/whisper</item>
        <item>airtable-cli — Cheap research repo if Dovetail is overkill. https://airtable.com/developers/web/api</item>
        <item>productboard API — Map opportunities → features. https://developer.productboard.com</item>
        <item>n8n / make — Cron the daily/weekly discovery loops. https://n8n.io</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="services">
      <list>
        <item>Dovetail (SaaS, Yes REST) — Best-in-class research repository, taggable.</item>
        <item>Condens (SaaS, Yes REST) — Cheaper Dovetail alternative.</item>
        <item>Productboard (SaaS, Yes REST) — Native opportunity-solution tree support.</item>
        <item>Pendo (SaaS, Yes REST) — In-app surveys + analytics in one.</item>
        <item>Hotjar (SaaS, Limited REST read) — Recordings + heatmaps; agents consume not control.</item>
        <item>Maze (SaaS, Yes REST) — Rapid unmoderated testing for weekly cadence.</item>
        <item>User Interviews (SaaS, Yes REST) — Source recurring participants automatically.</item>
        <item>Reveal (OSS, Partial) — Self-host research repo.</item>
        <item>PostHog (OSS/SaaS, Yes REST) — Open-source product analytics; agent-controllable.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Tag every interview snippet to an opportunity in a single repo. Without tagging, continuous discovery is just continuous chatter.</item>
        <item>Recruit a rolling panel of 30-50 users with rotation; never let the same 5 dominate.</item>
        <item>Ship one experiment per sprint, even tiny ones — cadence beats perfection.</item>
        <item>Combine interviews + behavioural data + support tickets for triangulation; one source alone is biased.</item>
        <item>Maintain an opportunity-solution tree (Teresa Torres) and require new ideas to attach to a node.</item>
        <item>Hold a monthly "what changed in user behaviour" review using analytics diffs, not anecdotes.</item>
        <item>Time-box weekly interviews to 30 minutes and 5-7 questions; longer sessions degrade signal.</item>
        <item>Keep a "decisions" log per quarter linking shipped features to discovery insights — this is the leakage check.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Synthesis agents over-summarise: many distinct quotes collapse into 2-3 generic themes. Set minimum themes and require evidence count per theme.</item>
        <item>Sentiment classifiers give false certainty on small samples; refuse confidence greater than 0.8 below n=15.</item>
        <item>Without explicit redaction, agents leak interviewee PII into shared tools. Add a scrubber step before pushing to any external repo.</item>
        <item>Behaviour anomaly detection trips on weekend/holiday seasonality; require comparison against trailing 4 weeks, not 7 days.</item>
        <item>Agents tend to recommend "schedule more interviews" as a remedy for any gap; force them to consider behavioural data and support tickets first.</item>
        <item>Continuous discovery agents running 24/7 produce alert fatigue; route digests to humans only on threshold breaches.</item>
        <item>Translation drift: interviewing in non-English languages and translating via LLM loses nuance; keep originals in the repo.</item>
        <item>Long-context cost: do not feed full transcripts every week. Index once, retrieve relevant chunks per query.</item>
        <item>Human checkpoint mandatory before treating an opportunity as validated; LLMs are credulous about user statements that contradict observed behaviour.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/check-leakage.py" purpose="Python script: flags releases unlinked to a research opportunity; fails when leakage exceeds 30%."/>
    </templates>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.producttalk.org"/>
      <link href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/continuous-discovery/"/>
      <link href="https://researchops.community"/>
      <link href="https://www.productboard.com/glossary/opportunity-solution-tree/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
